model_text_dct = {
    0: "The goal of this analysis was to provide insight into the effects of clean water on education rates. Given this, the observed R2 value of 0.231 is low but expected – there are undoubtedly other factors that play a more direct role in education rates, such government systems, income levels, availability of schools, cultural phenomena, and other factors.",
    1: "Also of note is the low count of rows in the final dataset. Due to the presence of NaNs from the JMP data source, and the decision to not engage in imputation, only 43.1% of countries are represented. This could lead to a gap in the model missing valuable information from countries that would add to its explanatory power.",
    2: "Still, the model produced two statistically significant features, which may capture two highly relevant signals: one signal captures the variance around “no” clean water, and the other signal captures the variance around “better” clean water.",
    3: "There is some nuance in which features specifically have statistical significance. The continuous “none” feature had the most extreme test statistical, which suggests it is the complete absence of water – not the limited availability of it – that has the most impact on education rates. In comparison, the continuous “limited” feature was not significant, with a test statistical of -0.148 and a p-value of 0.882.",
    4: "However, without the “limited” water features, uncaptured signal still exists in the large number of countries that have very good access to clean water, and generally higher education rates. Many of these countries scored a 0% on “limited”, meaning their access to clean water is 100% even at the better measure of availability. When a country is part of this group, the model suggests that its education rate increases by a whopping 21.86 points. This feature – “limited”, binary – had the largest coefficient, and was statistically significant at a p-value of 0.026; it captures the variance around countries with better water supply and high education rates.",
    5: "This analysis concludes that when it comes to “no” access to clean water, the model is highly sensitive to changes in percentage. A modest increase in clean water could have a real effect on education levels. For countries that have good access to clean water, the model implies that it’s those with the very best access that have strong education rates.",
}
